Property/Project Name: E Marginal Way S Preservation Project
Description: ***Need a ROW Address***SDOT’s E Marginal Way S Preservation Project (aka AAC E Marginal Way S) extends along E Marginal Way S from 1st Avenue S to the Tukwila border.  This section of E Marginal Way is a busy principal arterial that is part of the National Highway System (NHS), is classified as a T-2 road for freight (second highest rating by WSDOT), carries bus routes, and has bicycle lanes.  The purpose of the project is to extend the life of the existing pavement structure by 10 to 20 years.Overall, the project will include the following:•	Milling and overlaying the asphalt pavement, conducting base repairs, and sealing pavement cracks.•	Repairing and installing sidewalk, ADA curb ramps, curb bulbs, and signal loops.•	Installing a two-way buffered bike lane on the northeast side of E Marginal Way S from S River Street south to Corson Ave S•	Installing a multi-use path on the northeast side of E Marginal Way S from Corson Ave S south to the existing multi-use path that extends from the “Flume Property” south to 16th Avenue S (the Flume Property is roughly due north of Slip 4 of the Duwamish Waterway)•	Restriping the resurfaced road for traffic and rechannelizing portions of the road•	Installing street luminaires, and, at the Corson Avenue intersection, installing traffic signal strain poles.•	Removing or abandoning some inlets and catch basins and their connecting pipes and installing new inlets, catch basins and connecting pipes.•	Planting street trees.The work within the shoreline zone will generally consist of milling and overlaying the asphalt pavement, conducting base repairs, sealing pavement cracks, and installing a 35 foot wood pole to which a street luminaire and cables will be attached.

Pier 54 was renovated in 2015, and many of the piles were replaced at that time. Approximately 531 creosote-treated wood piles remain in place under the entire pier. KPFF Engineering has evaluated the piles and recommended which ones are in good condition and can be sequestered by wrapping, which should be repaired, and which can be removed altogether because they are no longer load-bearing.Some piles will be repaired by jacketing or stubbing; others will have protective technology installed, such as anodes or wraps. Pier 54 must also remove or sequester the remaining creosote-treated piles on the DNR parcel (approximately 250) by July 31, 2036, as a condition of their renewed DNR lease. NWEC proposes a 5-year maintenance plan that will allow Pier 54 to phase this work.

Construct Alterations to Existing Structure and Convert Duplex to Single Family Residence with Attached Accessory Dwelling Unit. — Our house was originally built as a single family home in 1916, and then converted to a duplex in 1920-1921, when a new entrance was added next to the original one, and a set a of stairs were built leading up the the second story unit. The new entrance and stairs were (and still are) walled off from the main floor living room. In order to connect the two units, we would now like to install a door in the wall between the base of these stairs and the main floor living room. This will allow us to access the second floor without going outside. We would also like to convert the use of our house from a duplex to a single family residence with an attached accessory dwelling unit on the upper floor. This project is Cured-In-Place-Pipe (CIPP) lining done entirely from the ground surface.  There would be no excavation as part of this work.  The CIPP process involves accessing the sewer mains at existing upstream and downstream maintenance holes (MHs) and inserting a resin pipe liner that is inflated to fit the shape of the existing pipe at these access points.  The liner is hardened (cured) using ultraviolet light and pipe connections are reinstated using a robotic tool. To complete this project, workers would need to access each MH. Site 25F is located within 200 ft of the shoreline and would need a shoreline exemption. This SPU project site crosses the Right-of-Way. Specific Scope:Site 25F (MH 020-154 to 020-153), asset #630801, 10” diameter, 65 linear feet, concrete sanitary sewer mainline. Install a CIPP liner along the entirety of the mainline from the upstream to the downstream MH and reinstate active laterals.

The local in-city electrical grid requires a connection between the westside (City of Seattle) and eastside (City of Tukwila) to meet energy demands, including forecasts for large increases in electricity usage, and a corresponding need for greater reliability of that electricity. Prior to 2003, an in-kind circuit provided connectivity via an overhead line, however attempts to reconstruct that line were stymied by a variety of factors. Electrification of fossil fuel power has already begun in the south Seattle area, and larger circuits with multiple paths of delivery, as provided by this circuit, are necessary to continue reducing fossil fuel use and to meet growing demands for clean energy. The project proposes installation of these circuits below the Duwamish River using trenchless methods, specifically (horizontal directional drilling [HDD]). This method avoids interference with other uses of the river (navigation, industry, habitat), and many potential environmental risks. The project will install three circuits beneath the Duwamish River between two Boeing owned properties (1) South Park property on the west and (2) Thompson/Isaacson property on the east. Practically and economically, the circuits must be installed beneath the river using trenchless construction techniques (HDD) because overhead placement of the circuits is not possible within the height restrictions imposed by the U.S. Coast Guard, U.S. Army Corps of Engineers (USACE), and Federal Aviation Administration. Open-cut installation beneath the riverbed is not practical from a construction standpoint, and would be too environmentally disruptive, with a high degree of risk. The lines must also be greater than 10 feet below the authorized dredge depth (-15 feet MLLW or -17.33 NAVD 88) to accommodate USACE dredging of the waterway, and to meet safety and engineering requirements.  The crossing includes three circuits that will be placed in three 32-inch diameter HDPE or PVC casing pipes. Once the casings are in place, a conduit bundle consisting of six 6-inch PVC conduit and one 4-inch conduit will be sliplined inside the casing. The conduit bundles will terminate at the HDD pit at each end. Connections will be established from the HDD pits to the existing grid within adjacent road rights-of-way, utilizing either overhead or underground routes. All connections will be situated entirely in upland areas.

***Plan Review Required*** We have had a lot line survey and geotech report completed and the geotech did a study for the client Kerry Kahl. In the report the geotech recommended we place retaining walls with geotech fabric to add to the stability of the slope. as noted below:  Any slope in Seattle that has an inclination of 40 percent or more and a height of 10 feet or more is considered a Steep Slope Erosion Hazard Area, per Seattle Municipal Code (SMC). A Steep Slope Erosion Hazard Area exists at the western portion of the subject site. SMC 25.09.090.8.1 states that development on Steep Slope Erosion Hazard Areas is prohibited unless "relief" can be obtained. Based on SMC 25.09.090.8.2.b, relief from the prohibition of development can be obtained for Steep Slope Erosion Hazard Areas when development is located on steep slope erosion hazard areas that were created by previous legal grading, if no adverse impact on the steep slope erosion hazard area will result.We believe that relief from development restrictions of the Steep Slope Erosion Hazard Area on the site. as noted in SMC 25.09.090.8.2.b. is warranted based on the following reasons:1. The portion of the site Steep Slope Erosion Hazard Area exceeding 10 feet in height includes a concrete retaining wall about 5 feet tall and slopes that have clearly been graded.2. The proposed engineered retaining walls will extend down to competent native soils and will completely stabilize the Steep Slope Erosion Hazard Area.In summary, it is our professional opinion from a geotechnical engineering standpoint that, provided recommendations in this study are followed, gaining relief from the Steep Slope Erosion Hazard Areas development standards of the SMC is appropriate for this project.Attached are all the supportive documents as well as a 2D design showing our rough proposed beckyard installation.

This is an application for an Exemption from the Shoreline Substantial Development Permit.  Seattle Public Utilities (SPU) owns and operates a wastewater collection system serving the City of Seattle.  As part of its Pump Station Rehabilitation Program, SPU proposes to construct improvements at its below-grade wastewater Pump Station 58 (PS58) at 1350 N Northlake Wy in the Fremont neighborhood of the City of Seattle.  This project would make comprehensive civil, mechanical, structural, electrical, and stormwater drainage improvements to PS58 to improve worker safety and to extend the useful life of the facility.  The scope also includes modifications to improve maintenance access, update instrumentation, and bring the station into compliance with current codes to the maximum extent feasible.  A code-compliant wet well ventilation system would be installed along with a new odor control system.  Exhaust fans would be located above-grade in cabinets.  Work would also replace approximately 58 lineal feet of an existing 6-inch diameter force main with new 6-inch diameter pipe.  The remaining approximately 122 lineal feet of the existing force main is in serviceable condition and would not be replaced or repaired.   Site work at PS58 would be limited to pavement surface restoration to accommodate excavations for ventilation piping, electrical conduit, and work on the force main, as well as above-grade mechanical and cabinet equipment.  Shallow excavations up to 4 feet are expected adjacent to the structure for ventilation, electrical, and force main replacement.  SPU plans to construct this project in 2026 or 2027. The entire project location is in the Urban Maritime Environment of the City of Seattle’s Shoreline Management District.  The Project is exempt from obtaining the Shoreline Substantial Development Permit at Seattle Municipal Code (SMC) 23.60A.020.C.1 as normal maintenance or repair of existing structures.

If the steel is left unprotected, permanent damage to the steel structure will occur over time, and can eventually lead to local or total collapse of the system.

A designated take-out area will be available for those looking for a quick and delicious meal on the go.Sourcing IngredientsWe are committed to quality and sustainability. Essential spices and specialty items will be imported to preserve the authenticity and integrity of our dishes.Restaurant Identity and MissionAzmarino bar and restaurant is more than just a place to eat—it’s a space for gathering, connection, and celebration. After the load test is complete, the parking lot pavement will be restored.

Property/Project Name: T30 Comprehensive Maintenance and Repair Program
Description: The Port of Seattle (Port) is requesting approval of a comprehensive repair and maintenance program (Program) to allow routine maintenance and repair of lawfully established structures, surfaces, and utilities, along the Port’s controlled shoreline. The activities will be conducted at specific locations as needed, with the Program being implemented over a ten (10) year period.The purpose of this Program is the development of one comprehensive shoreline exemption for each Port facility that would authorize a group of activities that meet the terms of one or more of the allowable shoreline exemptions pursuant to Chapter 23.60A.020 of the Seattle Shoreline Master Program (SMP). The Program will streamline the shoreline exemption approval process by reducing redundancy in conducting multiple individual reviews and managing multiple programmatic shoreline exemptions.
